    <div class="profile-section-block">
        <p class="profile-section-title">Foundation</p>
        <div class="profile-section-body"><p>The French colonial enterprise began not with settlement but with exploration. Jacques Cartier reached the Gulf of St. Lawrence in 1534, claiming territory for Francis I, but decades of religious civil war prevented meaningful colonisation. The First Empire took genuine root only in 1608, when Samuel de Champlain founded Quebec as the capital of New France and the centre of the fur trade. Jean-Baptiste Colbert, Louis XIV's finance minister, then systematised expansion as economic policy, establishing the French East India Company in 1664, building a powerful navy, and acquiring Saint-Domingue, which became the most profitable sugar colony in the Caribbean. By 1710, the First Empire stretched from Acadia along the St. Lawrence through the Great Lakes and down the Mississippi to Louisiana, covering over ten million square kilometres. The Seven Years' War destroyed it. The 1763 Treaty of Paris forced France to cede all of Canada and North American territory east of the Mississippi to Britain, reducing the empire to scattered Caribbean islands and five Indian trading posts. A second empire, founded with the 1830 invasion of Algiers, eventually surpassed the first in every measurable dimension.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="profile-section-block">
        <p class="profile-section-title">Socioeconomy</p>
        <div class="profile-section-body"><p>The economic logic of the First Empire rested on mercantilism and plantation slavery. Saint-Domingue alone produced forty percent of Europe's sugar and fifty percent of its coffee by the 1780s, making it the most revenue-generating colony in the world. The Second Empire operated on a different model, combining resource extraction with administrative integration. Algeria, designated a French department from 1848, attracted over one million European settlers, the pieds-noirs, creating a dual economy in which European landowners dominated export agriculture while indigenous Algerians worked marginal land under legal discrimination. Across West Africa, the mise en valeur doctrine framed colonial economies around producing raw materials for French industry: rubber from Indochina, phosphates from North Africa, cotton from the Sahel. The indigénat legal code imposed separate and inferior legal status on colonial subjects, institutionalising economic exclusion. The empire's ideological framing as a mission civilisatrice obscured a straightforward extractive relationship, a contradiction that French republican intellectuals increasingly struggled to rationalise as the twentieth century advanced.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="profile-section-block">
        <p class="profile-section-title">Military</p>
        <div class="profile-section-body"><p>French imperial military power was built on naval strength and specialised colonial forces. Colbert's naval construction programme made France the second maritime power in Europe by the late seventeenth century, enabling oceanic projection. The loss of naval supremacy to Britain, confirmed at the Battle of Lagos and Quiberon Bay in 1759, was the proximate military cause of the First Empire's collapse. The Second Empire relied heavily on the Foreign Legion, founded in 1831, and the tirailleurs, colonial infantry recruited from Senegal, Algeria, and Indochina who fought across both world wars and were paid at rates far below their French counterparts. Napoleon III built specialised colonial troops specifically for overseas campaigns, tripling French territorial holdings between 1852 and 1870. The catastrophic military failure that ended the Second Empire was Dien Bien Phu in May 1954, where General Vo Nguyen Giap's Viet Minh besieged and forced the surrender of a French garrison over fifty-six days, the most consequential colonial military defeat of the twentieth century. The Algerian War that followed, costing between 300,000 and 1.5 million Algerian lives across eight years, confirmed that no military solution existed for a colonial relationship the subject population had decided to end.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="profile-section-block">
        <p class="profile-section-title">Governance &amp; Law</p>
        <div class="profile-section-body"><p>France governed its two empires through structurally different models. The First Empire relied on chartered companies, appointed governors, and trading monopolies loosely supervised from Versailles, with little institutional coherence. The Second Empire developed a more systematic apparatus. Algeria was governed as an extension of France itself after 1848, with departments, prefects, and French civil law applying to European settlers while indigenous Algerians remained under the indigénat. Indochina was administered as five distinct territories under a governor-general from Hanoi. West and Equatorial Africa were organised into two vast federations headquartered at Dakar and Brazzaville. The 1946 constitution attempted to reframe this system as the French Union, theoretically transforming colonial subjects into French citizens with representation in Paris, but the reform was applied inconsistently and satisfied almost no one. De Gaulle's French Community of 1958 offered autonomy within a French framework, and when sub-Saharan African leaders including Sékou Touré of Guinea immediately chose full independence, the entire administrative edifice dissolved within two years.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="profile-section-block">
        <p class="profile-section-title">Global &amp; Regional Impact</p>
        <div class="profile-section-body"><p>The French Empire's most durable legacy is linguistic and institutional. French remains an official language in twenty-nine countries, the second most widely distributed official language on earth. The Napoleonic Code, exported across continental Europe during the First Empire's brief phase of continental dominance, fundamentally shaped the legal systems of France's European neighbours and, through them, of former colonies across Africa and the Americas. French educational institutions established under the colonial period produced the post-independence leadership class of much of Francophone Africa, creating the cultural dependency known as Françafrique that shaped African politics long after formal decolonisation. The Haitian Revolution of 1791 to 1804, which destroyed Saint-Domingue and produced the first Black republic in history under Toussaint Louverture and Jean-Jacques Dessalines, was itself a direct consequence of the First Empire's plantation economy and a transformative moment in Atlantic world history.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="profile-section-block">
        <p class="profile-section-title">Decline &amp; Fall</p>
        <div class="profile-section-body"><p>The First Empire collapsed through military defeat in 1763 and economic self-destruction through the Haitian Revolution. The Second Empire's dissolution was driven by nationalist resistance the French state could not suppress without costs that democratic public opinion would not sustain. Dien Bien Phu in 1954 ended French Indochina; seventeen sub-Saharan colonies became independent in 1960; the Évian Accords of March 1962 granted Algeria independence after eight years of war. Vanuatu's independence in 1980 completed the process. Unlike empires dissolved by external conquest, the French colonial empire collapsed because the ideological contradiction between France's republican identity and its colonial practice proved ultimately irresolvable. The French Empire's historical significance lies in its double arc: the only modern empire to collapse, rebuild, and peak again at greater scale, before being undone not by a rival power but by the incompatibility of its own values with its own conduct.</p></div>
      </div>

    <p class="profile-summary">France's imperial ambitions reached their peak under Napoleon, who redrew Europe's map, and again in the 19th century when France built the world's second-largest colonial empire.</p>

